	h4.cd Step 3. The Projector
	p.cd This step is very useful because it vastly improves the MRI experience for anyone. Instead of looking at a small screen through the mirror and seeing the claustrophobia-inducing tube in your peripheral vision, you see a view-filling stereoscopic image. Even for adults and older kids, this would be a much more relaxing and enjoyable experience.

	h4.cd Engineering Constraints
	p.cd There were many constraints in this design, such as designing a functional system without any electronic components, the tight space inside the MRI head coil, and patient comfort. To give a small sampling of how some of these constraints were overcome, here are a few design highlights:

	h5.cd Multiple Width Paddle System
	p.cd To prevent the phone or later projector screens from falling out, but to still fit within the tight constraints of the MRI head coil, I designed a paddle system using hidden rubber bands. The paddles are easy to press with one hand, while inserting the next part of the three step design. They quickly bounce back and even support the weight of an iPod when a user may vigorously shake their head from side to side.

	h5.cd Snap Together Component Design
	p.cd To make components interchangeable and to account for the limitations of 3D printing, I designed a piecewise method of designing, printing, and assembling the components. Using a round hole and a zero-tolerance octagon pin, each version of the design could be securely attached to the body and snap together.

